            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h1 id=\"get-started\">Get started</h1></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "1d0db38904205bec4d6f6f6a1f6cec3e",
            "console": [],
            "id": "MJUe",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "e4f28e6dc5cb66539fde4d4a986a0178",
            "console": [],
            "id": "vblA",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Let's start with a basic example. The task is <strong>text classification</strong>. In particular, we want to find out whether some social media comments contain hate speech or not.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">We define some examples to begin with:</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "8dd910c9f08f170284dbd3b1984db4d2",
            "console": [],
            "id": "bkHC",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "8e9a5a28ada5d15033a81100e317a083",
            "console": [],
            "id": "lEQa",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Now, we define the target function that performs the classification. Its outputs are the ones we will evaluate.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">The function must adhere to the <code>TargetFunction</code> protocol: take its <strong>named inputs</strong>, the <strong>prompt template</strong>, and an <strong>LM config</strong>, then return a <code>TargetOutput</code>. The harness unpacks <code>Example.inputs</code> as keyword arguments, so the parameter names here must match the dict keys.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "1ecd92ac164ccb27a64fcacc6040f5d5",
            "console": [],
            "id": "PKri",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "c2778f20b1015978c24cc8648c51a891",
            "console": [],
            "id": "Xref",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Now, lets define the moving parts under test. The three sweepable axes are the <strong>prompt template</strong>, the <strong>LM config</strong> (model, generation kwargs, optional output schema), and the target function itself.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "1fd53429ced3b6a4d70e3af1f9d2684b",
            "console": [],
            "id": "SFPL",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "ff88d5a803e95fed4dc968fccc3e4ce6",
            "console": [],
            "id": "BYtC",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">With these ingredients, we can already run a trial: execute the target function with one of the examples and the config under test.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "d51b2307c0e00a7f0e52738d3ae59c83",
            "console": [
                {
                    "mimetype": "text/plain",
                    "name": "stdout",
                    "text": "is_hate=True reason=\"The comment explicitly insults someone's appearance in a derogatory manner, which can be considered a form of personal attack and hate speech.\"\n",
                    "type": "stream"
                }
            ],
            "id": "RGSE",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "05bd67cf3a5dc1f7b6293f3827a91016",
            "console": [],
            "id": "Kclp",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Now that our trial run successfully, we can jump into the quality measurements.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Let's define a silly metric that simply compares the output from the function for the given example against the reference (our truth value).</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">For this, we do not need an LLM judge. A <code>ProgrammaticMetric</code> whose scorer follows the <code>ProgrammaticScorer</code> protocol is more than enough. We define the possible values using the <code>Ordinal</code> scale.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "a1e27124fda173a912dde500b4aaccc7",
            "console": [],
            "id": "emfo",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "42d29cf768ff9d0f83891d3b2c29dede",
            "console": [],
            "id": "Hstk",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Finally, we can just score the trial against the metric.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "a396312280856eeafaf9d139d245d91e",
            "console": [],
            "id": "nWHF",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/html": "<pre class='text-xs'>Score(raw=True, normalized=1.0, reason=&#x27;Output matches the reference&#x27;)</pre>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "71b22e66e9eea86e8116ae1a1a561aea",
            "console": [],
            "id": "iLit",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">For the sake of playing, we could also make an LLM Judge that evaluates the same and gives a brief explanation. You can use the default one or create one that adheres to the <code>LLMJudgeScorer</code> protocol. Judge metrics use the <code>LLMJudgeMetric</code> variant — they carry their own <code>LMConfig</code> and judge prompt template.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "2dd22bbf3310bb2dc2f8f587a1d0287c",
            "console": [],
            "id": "ZHCJ",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/plain": ""
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "34f6d898bb0d7751df989373e1f462ff",
            "console": [],
            "id": "ROlb",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Lets evaluate it on the same example and see what the Judge thinks about the system output.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "683e4603d07befe1ba1cd035329ac08e",
            "console": [],
            "id": "qnkX",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "application/vnd.marimo+mimebundle": {
                            "image/png": "data:image/png;base64,",
                            "text/html": "<pre class='text-xs'>Score(raw=True, normalized=1.0, reason=&quot;The result obtained from the LLM function is correct. The comment &#x27;I think you are pretty ugly&#x27; is indeed identified as hate speech, which aligns with the golden-standard expected reference of &#x27;True&#x27;. The reasoning provided by the LLM is also sound, as it explains that the comment is a derogatory personal attack.&quot;)</pre>"
                        }
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "code_hash": "b5a3de1affb0c9f25faf418019a2c434",
            "console": [],
            "id": "TqIu",
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "data": {
                        "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Finally, we can make a full run: execute our <code>detect_hate</code> target function on all the examples from our dataset and evaluate our two metrics on the outputs.</span></span>"
                    },
                    "type": "data"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
